    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1900-08-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1900-08-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="433"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d433">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Choate</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-08-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 24, 1900</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 387.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report that on the 23d
                    instant I received your cable instructions of the 22d instant,<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d433fn3">Circular telegram printed ante, <ref target="#pg_302">p.
                            302</ref>.</note> embodying telegrams from Earl Li Hung Chang, received
                    through the Chinese minister in Washington, urging the suspension of hostilities
                    in China and the appointment of an envoy to negotiate. Immediately upon its
                    receipt I addressed a note to Her Majesty’s minister for foreign affairs, dated
                    the 23d instant.</p>
                <p>I have the honor to be, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Joseph H. Choate.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
